Here’s what caught our attention on Wednesday: 1.August consumer inflation South Africa’s headline consumer inflation slowed to 4.9% year-on-year in August from 5.1% in July, data from Statistics South Africa showed on Wednesday. On a month-on-month basis, inflation contracted 0.1% in August after rising from 0.8% in July. 2.Astral Foods expects strong delivery of results Poultry producer, Astral Foods said in a trading statement that it expects earnings per share for the 12 months ended September 30, 2018, to increase by at least 80% to 3 506 cents, compared to the 1 948 cents in 2017. The company’s headline earnings per share is also expected to rise by at least 85% to 3 513 cents from 1 899 cents in 2017. Astral Foods attributes the strong delivery mainly to the improved profits reported in the first half of 2018. Results are expected to be released on November 19, 2018. 3.Pan African Resources results Gold mining company, Pan African Resources says it is on par with its gold production target of 170 000 ounces for the 2019 financial year. For the year ended June 30, 2018, it has however reported a decrease in headline earnings per share from continuing operations to  18.71 cents and a decrease in headline earnings to R229.1 million from R315.6 million the previous year.  No dividend is being declared for the period. 4.Progress on Sassa grants D-day for the Post Office to begin its social grant payments is around the corner, however, a new problem has surfaced and the process promises not to be smooth. In a report to the court, the panel assessing the process says that the fees charged by the Post Office is higher than those charged by Cash Paymaster Services (CPS). Moneyweb is reporting that the panel says that the fee of R51.77 is still above the R51 recommended  by National Treasury to CPS. Read: Post Office slammed for sky-high social grant payment fees 5.Katenge Tubular Construction under investigation Katenge Tubular Construction is being investigated by the Directorate for Priority Crime Investigation for its alleged involvement in fraud and corruption. Moneyweb is reporting that the company illegally paid R25 million to the Industrial Development Corporation in settlement of a loan facility. The board, as well as its BEE partner, had no knowledge of the deal. Read: Police investigate Tubular directors for fraud and corruption